GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 2



Introduction

GETCERTS is an X.509 certificate external environment (callable
library) module for Rexx. GETCERTS is driven by ADDRESS commands from
a Rexx program. In turn, GETCERTS inventories the RACF certificate
database and populates Rexx stem variables with most of the details of
the certificates in the RACF database. Similarly, GETCERTS will
inventory the RACF keyrings and returns their details to the Rexx
program. GETCERTS has no user interface beyond the ADDRESS command
environment and a printable listing; it is intended that the invoking
Rexx program would display or process the certificate information in
some suitable manner.

Overview of the Hypothetical Rexx Program
The concept is an ISPF application that would provide an advanced
X.509 certificate display on z/OS. In this paper I will refer to the
ISPF application as the Rexx program.

In addition, we might make GETCERTS available to the z/OS community as
a standalone CBT application. Users could develop their own
certificate reports or other applications as they chose.

In the following discussion I will reference the sample Rexx EXEC,
TGETCERT.

The envisioned ISPF application, the Rexx program, would start by
installing GETCERTS as a Rexx environment.  That process, and the
basic calls to GETCERTS using Rexx ADDRESS, are documented below under
Loading and Calling GETCERTS, and illustrated in the sample Rexx
script, TGETCERT, the Rexx program would start by calling the CERTSUMM
function, which is a prerequisite to any other functions.

The Rexx program would start by displaying a panel modeled after the
SDSF job displays. Each detail line of the display would represent one
certificate. The user could scroll up and down, and/or left and right.
The fields to be displayed would be chosen at the discretion of the
Rexx programmer, selected from the fields listed below under CERTSUMM.
Some of the fields may be as wide as 67 characters, so the Rexx
program would probably truncate them and/or allow user-variable column
widths similar to what SDSF does. The display of some fields might be
deferred, at the discretion of the implementer, to any Certificate
Detail request.

A primary command would let the user alternatively display keyrings,
one per detail line. To obtain the data for the display, the Rexx
program would call the RINGSUMM function. RINGSUMM returns only five
Rexx stem variables, so the panel design would be somewhat simpler
(although one of the fields, the keyring name, may be up to 237
characters wide, and may contain special characters).

GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 3

An important concept is certificate and keyring index numbers.  An
index number is an integer, starting with 1, that is used as the tail
of the various compound variables for the certificate or keyring.
(Stemname.0 contains the count of tails starting from 1, in accordance
with the typical Rexx convention.) The index number is also used by
GETCERTS to identify other certificates or keyrings, such as in the
CONCERT# keyring variable, which lists the index numbers of the
certificates connected to the ring, separated by blanks. Thus
WORDS(CONCERT#.tail) would give the number of certificates connected
to the keyring with a keyring index of tail, and WORD( CONCERT#.tail,
1) would be the index number of the first certificate connected to the
keyring. The sample Rexx script TGETCERT illustrates this logic. (All
GETCERT returned variables with stem names ending in # are similar
lists of index numbers.)

It is envisioned that the certificate and keyring primary displays
would support various line commands similar to the SDSF S line command
(subject to the discretion of the the Rexx program author). The
anticipated commands, and a brief summary of how they might be
implemented, are listed below.

Certificate Line Command Functions:

  o List Detail. This would be implemented by performing the CERTDETL
function, passing the index number of the certificate. I will leave it
to the discretion of the implementor how to display the various
returned data, including any data deferred from the primary
certificate display.

  o List Chain. This would be implemented by following the certificate
chain in ISSUER# for each certificate. Note that a certificate could
have multiple issuers. It is unlikely, but it is possible. There is
an example of how a List Chain would work in the sample Rexx EXEC,
TGETCERT.

  o List Dependents. This is the reverse of List Chain and is
implemented by displaying the certificates listed in the
certificates LEAF#. The sample script, TGETCERT, has examples.

  o List Connected Keyrings. This function would require that a
RINGSUMM function had been called. The list of connected keyrings is
found in KEYRING#.



GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 4



Keyring Line Command Functions

  o List Connected Certificate Detail. This function would be
implemented by calling the RINGCONN function and displaying the
returned data. It would be good if the Certificate line commands were
then available so one might do a List Detail, or List Chain, etc.

Loading and Calling GETCERTS
GETCERTS is invoked by a Rexx program as a Rexx ADDRESS
environment. The Rexx program would install GETCERTS as a Rexx
environment using the separate program EZSUBCOM.

EZSUBCOM must be available to the Rexx program. It may reside in
ISPLLIB.  GETCERTS must reside in the MVS content management chain
(STEPLIB, etc.) or in the load library or load library concatenation
identified by loadlbdd in the statements below. ISPLLIB is not
searched for GETCERTS. EZSUBCOM is separately documented but the
following is an overview of using EZSUBCOM to install GETCERTS as a
Rexx environment.

EZSUBCOM must be invoked with Rexx CALL; it cannot be invoked with
ISPF SELECT PGM.

Initialization

ADDRESS ISPEXEC "LIBDEF ISPLLIB DATASET ID(ezsubcom.loadlib) STACK"
ADDRESS TSO "ALLOC FI(loadlbdd) DA(getcerts.loadlib) SHR"
ADDRESS TSO 'ALLOC FI(GCPRINT) desired alloc operands'
Call 'EZSUBCOM' 'ADDLESUB', 'GETCERTS', , , 'loadlbdd'

GCPRINT may be allocated to the terminal, to DUMMY or to a dataset as
the the Rexx program author prefers. It must be allocated before the
call to EZSUBCOM ADDLESUB. If GETCERTS cannot open GCPRINT then the
ADDLESUB call will fail.  GETCERTS opens GCPRINT RECFM=VBA, LRECL=133.

Rexx will load EZSUBCOM from ISPLLIB but not GETCERTS. If GETCERTS is
not in the STEPLIB chain then you must allocate a DD to the
appropriate load library and pass it as a parameter to EZSUBCOM as
shown above.

CALL EZSUBCOM returns its result in the Rexx special variable
RESULT. RESULT is a string consisting of a return code 0, 4, 8, 12 or
16 following the usual MVS conventions and, if the return code is
non-zero, a string describing the error or warning condition.


GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 5

Sample Rexx code:

Retvalue = RESULT
Parse var Retvalue retcode errmsg
If retcode <> 0 Then Do
  Say 'EZSUBCOM' retcode errmsg
  If retcode > 4 Then /* Deal with error */
  End

Information Retrieval

See Certificate and Ring Information Retrieval and Retrieving Error
and Other Messages.

Termination
CALL 'EZSUBCOM' 'DELETE', 'GETCERTS'
ADDRESS TSO 'FREE FI(GCPRINT)'
ADDRESS TSO 'FREE FI(loadlbdd)'

See Initialization above for EZSUBCOM return result information.

Certificate and Ring Information Retrieval

Linkage

ADDRESS GETCERTS function parameters

The various functions and parameters are documented in detail below.

ADDRESS returns an integer return code in the Rexx special variable
RC. If the CEEPIPI call returns a non-zero value (which in our
experience is unlikely) then EZSUBCOM returns the CEEPIPI return code;
otherwise EZSUBCOM returns the return code from the module. CEEPIPI
subroutine invocation return codes are documented here:

https://www.ibm.com/docs/en/zos/3.2.0?topic=csis-return-codes . All
of the non-zero values are should-not-occur conditions.

Return Codes and Associated Messages

GETCERTS logs all error and warning conditions to the GCPRINT data
set. GETCERTS returns :

     0    Successful function, no error or warning conditions detected
     4    One or more warning conditions detected.
     8    One or more error conditions detected in the RACF
          certificate store.
    12    One or more error conditions detected in the parameters
          passed on ADDRESS or in executing them.
    16    Fatal error condition in GETCERTS. GETCERTS could not
          continue.  Contents of Rexx variables may not be valid.




GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 6

In addition, for non-zero RC values, GETCERTS returns in the Rexx
special variable RESULT a printable error message for the first
detected condition that caused the error of that severity. In other
words, if GETCERTS returns a 12 in RC then RESULT will contain an
error message corresponding to the condition that caused the severity
12 error.

Retrieving Error and Other Messages

GETCERTS can also return error and other messages in Rexx compound
variables, GC_MSGS.n, where n is an integer following the usual
Rexx convention, with a count in GC_MSGS.0. To control the return of
messages, specify MSGLEVEL nn|NO on any ADDRESS command. See Common
Parameters below. The GC_MSGS stem is always GC_MSGS; it is not
affected by any PREFIX specification.

The GC_MSGS stem is populated cumulatively by each ADDRESS
command. If your first ADDRESS command returns GC_MSGS.1 and
GC_MSGS.2, then any messages returned by the next ADDRESS command
would start from GC_MSGS.3. If you want to process only the messages
from one ADDRESS command then you should save the value of GC_MSGS.0
before that ADDRESS command and only process GC_MSGS tails starting
from that value plus one.

Most certificate-related error messages, if any, tend to be generated
on a CERTSUMM call. Use caution if you specify both VERBOSE and
MSGLEVEL 0:  GETCERTS may generate thousands of informational VERBOSE
messages.

GETCERTS messages follow the usual IBM and z/OS message conventions.
The following are examples of an informational, warning, error and
severe error message respectively:

CMC0058I GETCERTS() subroutine entered with ADDRESS GETCERTS
         'CERTSUMM PREFIX C_'
CMC0011W The following certificates share a common Subject Key ID,
         which may cause validation problems.
         Key ID: 35333A37393A42463A35413A41413A32423A34413A43
CMC0048E Should not occur: ring JES2UID/FTP.Key.Ring contains
         unknown certificate SYS06 'CMC Endpoint'
CMC0041S The command token PERFIX is not recognized

Returned Certificate Information

Certificate and keyring data is returned to the Rexx program in Rexx
variables. The Rexx program may specify name prefixes a character
string to be prepended to the defined variable names.

GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 7



Data Formats
Date and Time Format. Dates and times are returned in ISO 8601
(2026-02- 21T11:46:33): it's a standard, it's sortable, it's
unambiguous for international customers, and it's easy to truncate
to 10 characters if time is not needed.  Certificate timstamps are
formatted as UTC.

Hexadecimal Format. Unpunctuated uppercase hex is common on the
mainframe:  08C6A634815E296535A4  ¦ Uppercase hex with colon as a byte
separator is used by RACF: 7A:2B:6A:F3:C4:91:DF:D3... in some places
and unpunctuated lowercase hex in others. Lowercase hex with colon as
a byte separator is used by OpenSSL:  08:c6:a6:34:81:5e:29:65:21:35:a4
 ¦ Gskkyman uses uppercase hex with blank as a byte separator in some
places and unpunctuated lowercase hex in others.  GETCERTS follows
RACF's lead and uses 7A:2B:6A:F3:C4:91:DF:D3... but I am open to
suggestions.

True/False Format. TRUE and FALSE are returned as 1 and 0 for
convenient usage from Rexx. The Rexx program might choose to display
the values as TRUE/FALSE, YES/NO, TRUST/NOTRUST or otherwise as the
programmer chose.

GETCERTS Functions

The Rexx program will call the CERTSUMM (Get Certificate Summary) and
RINGSUMM (Get Ring Summary) functions once and display summary
information.  Then, if the user asks for detail for a particular
certificate, the Rexx program will call CERTDETL (Get Certificate
Detail) for that certificate. Or if a user asks for the connected
certificates for a particular keyring then the Rexx program would call
RINGCONN (Get Keyring Connected Certificates).

If the user wished to refresh the certificate or ring data it should
be possible to call the CERTSUMM and/or RINGSUMM functions again, but
this has not been tested.

Summary information is returned in a set of Rexx compound variables
with a defined stem name and a numerical tail.

For example, assuming a certificate variable prefix of C_, the label
information for the certificates will be returned in C_LABEL.1,
C_LABEL.2, C_LABEL.3 and so forth, with a count of certificates in
C_LABEL.0. Similarly, the    not after   date for the certificates
will be returned in C_NOTAFTER.1, C_NOTAFTER.2, C_NOTAFTER.3, and so
forth.

In this paper I will refer to the Rexx stem variable tail value (1, 2
and 3 in the examples above) as the certificate's or keyring's
index number.

GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 8



The detail information would similarly be returned in a set of Rexx
variables, but the detail variables would for the most part be simple
Rexx variables. The certificate detail data would apply to only the
one certificate so there would be no need for compound qualification.
The exception would be several pieces of detail information that might
repeat a variable number of times. That information would be returned
in compound variables using the usual .1, .2, .3 and .0 convention.

Why not simply return all of the certificate's or keyring's data in
the summary variables? The main reason is that some of the detail data
repeats in stem variables with numeric tails. As the summary data
already repeats in stem variables with numeric tails, that would imply
double numeric tails variables like C_SAN.37.3 for the third SAN
(Subject Alternate Name) for certificate number 37. I feel that would
be confusing.

Why a separate RINGINFO call? Because ring retrieval requires
additional permissions beyond those required for certificate
retrieval, and some users might not have those permissions and would
prefer not to get security violations.

Detailed Description of GETCERTS Functions

Common Parameters

The common parameters are

[MSGLEVEL nn|NO] [PREFIX prefix] [VERBOSE]

These parameters may be specified with any of the functions.

MSGLEVEL nn|NO specifies the severity level of messages to be returned
in the GC_MSGS compound variable. Specify where an integer  or N.; NO
indicates that no messages are to be returned. nn is a severity level:
if you specify 0 then all messages generated by GETCERTS are returned;
if you specify 4 then warning and error messages are returned but not
informational messages; if you specify 8 then only error messages are
returned; and if you specify 12 then only severe error messages are
returned. Severe error messages always diagnose programming or similar
errors such as a mis-spelled command token. If you omit MSGLEVEL then
it defaults to MSGLEVEL 8. See Retrieving Error and Other Messages
above.

PREFIX prefix specifies an optional prefix to be prepended to the
returned Rexx variable names. For example, assuming a certificate
variable prefix of C_, the label information for the certificates will
be returned in C_LABEL.1, C_LABEL.2, C_LABEL.3 and so forth, with a
count of certificates in C_LABEL.0. The prefix may be any length but
prefixes longer than four characters may have a slight negative effect
on performance.

GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 9




VERBOSE specifies that additional informational messages are to be
output to GCPRINT by GETCERTS. The VERBOSE output is potentially
voluminous.

CERTSUMM     Get Certificate Summary

CERTSUMM retrieves certificate summary information for all
certificates.

ADDRESS GETCERTS CERTSUMM [common parameters]

CERTSUMM is required as the first parameter. It specifies the
certificate summary function.

See also Common Parameters above.

The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any
order.

The CERTSUMM function requires the following RACF permissions:

  o READ authority to IRR.RADMIN.RLIST (or IRR.RADMIN.*) in the
    FACILITY class.
  o READ authority to CSFOWH in the CSFSERV class; or
    CSF.CSFSERV.AUTH.CSFOWH.DISABLE resource
    profile defined in the XFACILIT class.

And either

  o If the *.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST profile or any
    userid.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST profile exists in the
    RDATALIB class, then READ authority to the
    *.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST profile.

  o Otherwise UPDATE authority to IRR.DIGTCERT.LISTRING in the
    FACILITY class.

The CERTSUMM function may be invoked as many times as the Rexx program
wishes. It must be invoked before any other function.

Rexx variables set by CERTSUMM are listed in the table below. The Rexx
stem names are prefixed as described above. The Rexx program
might choose to defer some of these fields to any detail display.




GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 10



Rexx Stem
Description Notes

AUTHKID
Authority Key See Hexadecimal Format above.

CAUSAGE
From basic 1 if CA:TRUE; 0 if CA: FALSE constraints

CERTDADD
Date certificate See Date and Time Format above. No
added to RACF time; only date. Time is recorded as
00:00:00.

CERTUADD
RACF ID of user 1 to 8 characters. Never irrcerta or
who actually added irrsitec. Not necessarily the same as the
certificate to RACF certificate  s CERTUSER.

CERTUSER
Certificate owner 1 to 8 characters. CERTAUTH and SITE
returned as irrcerta and irrsitec (lower
case) respectively.

FINGERPR
SHA-256 fingerprint 32 bytes, reported as 63 characters, as
of the certificate reported by RACF. See Hexadecimal Format above.

ISSUER
Full issuer name May be up to 2048 characters ISSUER# Index
number(s) of Normally at most one issuer, but issuer certificates
because of cross-signing, expired intermediates and other somewhat
unusual circumstances a certificate may have multiple issuers. (See
footnotes under Overview of the Hypothetical Rexx Program.) Multiple
Issuer index numbers are separated by blanks. Empty string if no
issuer certificate present.  Empty string for self-signed
certificates.

ISSUER$
Short issuer name Issuer name shortened to most significant
RDN by algorithm. Up to 67 characters, but the Rexx program may
display less if so chooses.

KEYALGO
Public key Name such as rsaEncryption algorithm

KEYLEN
Private key length in bits

KEYTYPE
Private key type Key type and location, such as    RSA (in
RACF)

LABEL
Certificate label 1 to 32 characters. May include embedded
special characters, including blanks and quotes. Quotes are not
doubled by GETCERTS.

LEAF#
Index numbers of Empty string if none. Multiple index
certificates signed numbers separated by blanks.  Self not by
this certificate included for self-signed certificates.

GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 11



Rexx Stem
Description Notes

NOTAFTER
Certificate See Date and Time Format above.  expiration date
and time

NOTBEFOR
Certificate start See Date and Time Format above.  date and
time

PRIVKEY
Is there a private 1 if private key in RACF, 0 if not.2 key

SELFSIGN
Certificate is self- 1 if self-signed; 0 if not signed

SERIAL
Certificate serial See Hexadecimal Format above.  number

SIGALGO
Signature algorithm A name like sha256WithRSAEncryption
SUBJECT Full subject name May be up to 2048 characters SUBJECT$ Short
subject name Subject name shortened to most significant RDN by
algorithm. Up to 67 characters, but the Rexx program may display less
if so chooses.

SUBJKID
Subject Key See Hexadecimal Format above.  identifier

THUMBPR
SHA-1 Thumbprint 20 bytes, formatted as 39 characters (used by
Windows). See Hexadecimal Format above.

TRUST
Certificate trust 1 if trusted; 0 if not status

RINGSUMM     Get Keyring Summary

RINGSUMM retrieves keyring summary information below for all rings and
certificate ring connections. May not precede the CERTSUMM call.

ADDRESS GETCERTS RINGSUMM [common parameters]

RINGSUMM is required as the first parameter. It specifies the keyring
summary function.

See also Common Parameters above.




GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 12



The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any
order.

RINGSUMM requires the following additional RACF permissions:

  o UPDATE authority to IRR.DIGTCERT.LISTRING in the FACILITY class.
  o If any keyring profiles exist in the RDATALIB class, then READ
    authority to *.*.LST in RDATALIB.

The RINGSUMM command may not be invoked before CERTSUMM, and may only
be invoked once after each CERTSUMM without an intervening CERTSUMM
invocation.

Rexx variables set by RINGSUMM are listed in the tables below. The
Rexx program might choose to defer displaying some of these fields to
any certificate detail function.

Additional certificate variables, indexed by certificate    index
number  :

Rexx Stem
Description Notes

KEYRING#
Keyring index Integers separated by blanks. Empty numbers of
string if none or if Get Ring Summary connected keyrings has not been
called. Sorted into ascending keyring index sequence.


Keyring variables, indexed by a keyring index number as a tail;
for example, RINGUSER.9. The .0 tails contain a count of elements.

Rexx Stem
Description Notes

CONCERT#
Certificate index Zero or more integers separated by blanks,
numbers of sorted into ascending sequence. An empty connected string
if no connected certificates. The Rexx certificates. program may
access the userid, label and so forth of the certificates as desired
using the returned certificate index number and the appropriate Rexx
variables.

NAME
Keyring name 1 to 237 characters. May contain lowercase and
special characters.

RINGDADD
Date keyring added See Date and Time Format above. No time;
to RACF only date. Time is recorded as 00:00:00.

RINGUADD
RACF ID of user who 1 to 8 characters. Never irrcerta or
irrsitec. Not actually added necessarily the same as the Keyring's
keyring to RACF RINGUSER.

RINGUSER
Keyring owner 1 to 8 characters. Never irrcerta or irrsitec.


GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 13



CERTDETL     Get Certificate Detail

CERTDETL retrieves certificate detail information for one certificate,
specified by certificate index number. The function may be called
multiple times to retrieve information for multiple certificates.

ADDRESS GETCERTS CERTDETL CERTINDX index [common parameters]

CERTDETL is required as the first parameter. It specifies the
certificate detail function.

CERTINDX index is required and specifies the certificate index number
of the certificate for which detail information is to be returned.

See also Common Parameters above.

The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any
order.

CERTDETL may only be invoked after CERTSUMM.

The certificate detail variables are stem variables following the
usual Rexx convention. Assuming no change in prefix, each call to the
CERTDETL function overwrites the variables from the previous call.

Rexx Description Notes

Variable

EXTUSAGE
Extended key usage Stem variable. May be multiple usages.
Character strings such as "Server Authentication", "Client
Authentication", "Code Signing", etc.

KEYUSAGE
Key usage Stem variable. May be multiple usages.  Character
strings such as "Digital Signature", "Content Commitment", "Key
Encipherment", etc.

SAN
Subject Alternative Stem variable; may be dozens or more. Format
Names DNS: www.foobar.com



RINGCONN     Get Keyring Connected Certificates

RINGCONN retrieves a list of connected certificates and their
attributes for one keyring, specified by keyring index number. The
function may be called multiple times to retrieve information for
multiple keyrings.

ADDRESS GETCERTS RINGCONN RINGINDX index [common parameters]

GETCERTS     Rexx Certificate Library for RACF   Page 14



RINGCONN is required as the first parameter. It specifies the ring
connections function.

RINGINDX index is required and specifies the keyring index number of
the keyring for which connection information is to be returned.

See also Common Parameters above.

The remaining parameters are optional and may be specified in any
order.

RINGCONN requires the following RACF permissions:

  o READ authority to <virtual ring owner>.IRR_VIRTUAL_KEYRING.LST
    in the FACILITY class.

RINGCONN may only be invoked after RINGSUMM and before invoking
another CERTSUMM. Any number of CERTDETL and/or RINGCONN commands may
precede a RINGCONN.

A list of connected certificates and their attributes are  returned as
Rexx compound variables with a numeric tail, following the usual
conventions. Each tail number represents the attributes of one
connected certificate. A keyring may have no connected certificates,
in which case all of the listed Rexx Stems will have a tail .0 with a
value of 0. Assuming no change in prefix, each call to the RINGCONN
function overwrites the variables from the previous call.

Rexx Stem
Description Notes

CERTIF#
Certificate index The Rexx program may access the userid,
label number  and so forth of the certificate as desired using the
returned certificate index number and the appropriate Rexx variables.

DEFAULT
Whether certificate 1 = default; 0 = not the default. Note
that a is the default on the keyring has at most one and may have no
keyring default certificate.

USAGE
Certificate usage on CERTAUTH, PERSONAL or SITE keyring




